02:52.267 --> 02:53.767
It's camp themed, see.

02:53.767 --> 02:56.267
A bonfire,
a pine tree, and a canoe.

02:56.267 --> 02:57.467
Uh-huh.

02:58.968 --> 03:00.801
Anything interesting?

03:03.968 --> 03:06.033
Anything interesting that
isn't from my mother?

03:07.567 --> 03:08.901
Or my father?

03:08.901 --> 03:11.067
You know, in a weird way
you've kind of got to admire

03:11.067 --> 03:13.267
their persistence, though.
I mean, how many people

03:13.267 --> 03:15.334
would continue to write and call
on a daily basis

03:15.334 --> 03:17.367
without any response
from you whatsoever?

03:17.367 --> 03:19.901
"Dear Kirs,
you ruined your life once.

03:19.901 --> 03:21.200
It's gonna happen again."

03:21.200 --> 03:22.801
"Dear Poodle,
the only thing this man

03:22.801 --> 03:24.167
has too offer you
is heartache."

03:25.567 --> 03:27.501
File these with the others,
would you?

03:30.133 --> 03:31.767
She's back.
Hey.

03:31.767 --> 03:34.000
Hey, girl.
Oh, we missed you.

03:34.000 --> 03:35.601
Me too.
Did you have a good time?

03:35.601 --> 03:37.467
Get a load of this.

03:37.467 --> 03:39.234
It was so much fun--
You're back.

03:39.234 --> 03:41.534
Hey! Poison ivy? Poison oak?
I'm clean.

03:41.534 --> 03:43.000
Hey, Jule, guess what?

03:43.000 --> 03:44.367
CHARLIE:
Wait a second.

03:44.367 --> 03:45.834
Have you--? Did y--?
Two inches.

03:45.834 --> 03:47.334
Anyway, I wanted
to tell you guys--

03:47.334 --> 03:49.868
Hey, are we cutting into this
because I skipped lunch?

03:49.868 --> 03:52.267
I told you you'd have a good
time and you didn't believe me.

03:52.267 --> 03:53.868
I met a boy.
What is that, a cigar?

03:53.868 --> 03:55.968
Uh, It's, um-- It's a canoe.

03:55.968 --> 03:57.868
BAILEY: Canoe. Huh?
JULIA: No kidding?

03:57.868 --> 03:59.200
Next time you
make the cake.

03:59.200 --> 04:01.234
I met a boy and I fell in love,
okay?

04:02.667 --> 04:03.968
I'm in love.

04:06.667 --> 04:09.434
Just thought you'd wanna know.

04:09.434 --> 04:12.601
Today, when he turned around
and saw it was you, I mean,

04:12.601 --> 04:15.701
the look on his face.
God. You know, just, God, heh.

04:15.701 --> 04:17.733
Yeah?
Yeah.

04:17.733 --> 04:18.901
So did you guys make plans?

04:18.901 --> 04:20.901
You should invite him
to the bonfire.

04:20.901 --> 04:23.667
Griffin's never planned
anything in his life.

04:23.667 --> 04:25.467
But he'll call.

04:25.467 --> 04:28.067
Probably from some
payphone somewhere.

04:28.067 --> 04:29.767
And he'll sound like
he just woke up

04:29.767 --> 04:31.534
or like he's totally bored.

04:31.534 --> 04:33.968
And then when
his quarter runs out,

04:33.968 --> 04:37.100
he'll say--
All casually, he'll say,

04:37.100 --> 04:39.567
"So, what are you doing later
because I was thinking--?"

04:39.567 --> 04:42.067
[ PHONE RINGS]
See, I told you.

04:42.067 --> 04:44.434
Hello?

04:44.434 --> 04:46.701
No.

04:46.701 --> 04:47.968
No.

04:47.968 --> 04:50.767
No, I-I don't want
to participate in any survey.

04:53.801 --> 04:55.667
He'll call.

04:56.834 --> 04:59.334
So this whole boyfriend thing,

04:59.334 --> 05:02.300
it's, um--
It's kind of out of the blue.

05:02.300 --> 05:05.200
I mean, you always seemed
sort of uninterested.

05:05.200 --> 05:08.501
Yeah. I know.
Go figure.

05:08.501 --> 05:11.300
Oh, he is just so cute.

05:11.300 --> 05:13.601
This is the absolute
best picture of us.

05:13.601 --> 05:15.334
You're not in this picture,
Claud.

05:15.334 --> 05:18.100
Well, we ripped it in half,
and he took the half with me.

05:18.100 --> 05:20.334
But, um, that's my arm.

05:20.334 --> 05:22.000
You know,

05:22.000 --> 05:24.200
it's really too bad Bailey
didn't get to meet Byron.

05:24.200 --> 05:26.000
Yeah. Byron's parents were,
like,

05:26.000 --> 05:28.133
pretty much
the first ones there.

05:28.133 --> 05:30.234
Bay missed them by,
like, 10 seconds.

05:30.234 --> 05:32.167
Ten seconds?
Hm.

05:32.167 --> 05:34.567
And he didn't want to wait
around to meet your family?

05:34.567 --> 05:36.267
He was in a rush.

05:36.267 --> 05:37.734
Hm, all those letters home,
Claud,

05:37.734 --> 05:39.467
and not one mention of this.

05:39.467 --> 05:41.033
What?
You think that's weird?

05:47.534 --> 05:50.667
It's like--
It's like you're this--

05:50.667 --> 05:52.801
This sea turtle

05:52.801 --> 05:55.501
because there's something
inside of you.

05:55.501 --> 05:57.000
Something unspoken.

05:57.000 --> 05:58.467
Exactly. Exactly.
This-- This--

05:58.467 --> 06:01.501
This unspoken voice
that just says,

06:01.501 --> 06:03.267
"Go back to the sea.

06:03.267 --> 06:04.801
Go back to the sea."

06:04.801 --> 06:06.667
Hm, isn't that romantic?

06:06.667 --> 06:08.067
Yeah.

06:08.067 --> 06:09.667
You're gonna be gone
for how long now?

06:09.667 --> 06:11.567
Six days.
Four days.

06:11.567 --> 06:13.534
Hey, I got stuff to do
to get ready for college.

06:13.534 --> 06:15.334
GINA:
Let me get this straight,
Willie.

06:15.334 --> 06:17.834
You're spending
the last few days of summer

06:17.834 --> 06:19.868
before you go off to school
alone

06:19.868 --> 06:21.100
with Bailey?

06:22.667 --> 06:25.567
That's--
That's, like, wow.

06:27.033 --> 06:28.934
Sorry. That's just--
Well, you wanna come?

06:29.968 --> 06:31.767
What? What--?

06:31.767 --> 06:33.968
W-what happened to this
being a guy thing, Will?

06:33.968 --> 06:36.567
Well, so now i-it's a two guys
and girlfriend thing.

06:36.567 --> 06:38.400
Hello? Wait a second.

06:38.400 --> 06:39.667
Yeah. Wait a second.
If you--

06:39.667 --> 06:41.234
If you think
I'm going down to Mexico

06:41.234 --> 06:43.534
with you and your girlfriend--
So Sarah goes too.

06:43.534 --> 06:45.167
Yeah. Damn right she goes too.

06:45.167 --> 06:46.167
Fine.
Fine.

06:46.167 --> 06:47.634
Great.
Great.

06:48.834 --> 06:49.968
Great.

06:51.534 --> 06:53.000
[DOORBELL RINGS]

06:53.000 --> 06:54.801
How much do you want to bet
it's the mailman

06:54.801 --> 06:56.501
with a letter bomb
from your folks?

07:00.133 --> 07:01.167
Ellie.

07:01.167 --> 07:03.400
I'm not talking to you.

07:03.400 --> 07:04.567
Charlie, who is it?

07:05.534 --> 07:06.601
Mom?

07:08.234 --> 07:09.934
What are you doing--?

07:09.934 --> 07:11.400
I thought about calling first,

07:11.400 --> 07:13.601
but I got tired
of being hung up on.

07:16.234 --> 07:18.434
Don't I, uh, get a hug?

07:18.434 --> 07:20.701
Not if you've come
to criticize.

07:20.701 --> 07:22.667
Charlie and I don't
want to hear it anymore.

07:22.667 --> 07:24.501
So you might as well
get used to it.

07:24.501 --> 07:26.901
Because what you see here
is the way it's gonna be.

07:26.901 --> 07:29.667
We love each other.
And, okay, yeah,

07:29.667 --> 07:31.801
so we're not getting married,
but we are together.

07:31.801 --> 07:33.267
So you just better
get used to it.

07:34.200 --> 07:35.968
That's not why I'm here.

07:37.100 --> 07:39.033
Then why are you here?

07:39.033 --> 07:40.667
Yeah. Why are you here?

07:41.801 --> 07:43.367
I'm here because

07:45.033 --> 07:47.534
I have no place else to go.

07:47.534 --> 07:49.400
Because my marriage is over.

07:49.400 --> 07:51.334
[***]

08:07.400 --> 08:08.968
[SIGHS]

08:15.834 --> 08:19.300
Hey, how's your mom doing?

08:19.300 --> 08:21.834
Oh, I still don't know
what my dad did,

08:21.834 --> 08:24.033
and she refuses
to let me call him.

08:24.033 --> 08:25.501
Men,

08:25.501 --> 08:28.167
they can be heartless bastards
sometimes, can't they?

08:29.801 --> 08:33.366
Byron, he claimed he forgot
to give me a goodbye present.

08:35.967 --> 08:38.299
His tennis bandanna.

08:38.299 --> 08:40.534
He must have stuck it
in my duffle last-minute.

08:41.667 --> 08:43.167
[SIGHS]

08:43.167 --> 08:45.868
He knows just how to toy
with my emotions.

08:47.000 --> 08:48.100
You know, Claud,

08:49.834 --> 08:52.100
I was remembering my first time
at sleep-away camp.

08:52.100 --> 08:53.801
I think I was exactly your age.

08:53.801 --> 08:56.300
Oh, yeah?
It's the best, huh?

08:56.300 --> 08:58.667
Yeah.

08:58.667 --> 09:02.868
Except when everyone
started coupling up,

09:02.868 --> 09:05.901
and I was kind of shy and--

09:05.901 --> 09:07.734
And totally boyfriendless.

09:07.734 --> 09:11.334
And-- And all I really
wanted was just to--

09:11.334 --> 09:13.701
To be like everyone else.

09:15.801 --> 09:17.734
So I started telling
the girls in my bunk

09:17.734 --> 09:19.734
all these stories about Keith

09:20.968 --> 09:24.501
my boyfriend back home,
who I totally made up

09:25.968 --> 09:30.601
just so I wouldn't feel
left out of everything.

09:30.601 --> 09:32.834
I can see why you'd have
to do something like that.

09:32.834 --> 09:36.501
I mean, hey, the peer pressure
at camp can be kind of intense.

09:37.400 --> 09:40.267
Exactly. Exactly.

09:40.267 --> 09:42.601
I just wish that
I had someone to tell me

09:42.601 --> 09:45.267
it was okay
not to have a boyfriend.

09:46.834 --> 09:50.701
That-- That-- That I didn't have
to make up stories or anything.

09:50.701 --> 09:52.934
That my time would come.

09:57.133 --> 09:58.868
You poor thing.

09:58.868 --> 10:01.100
I mean, how awful for you.

10:04.067 --> 10:06.300
[INHALES DEEPLY]

10:06.300 --> 10:08.400
It still smells like him.

10:14.367 --> 10:17.334
WILL AND BAILEY:
* La cucaracha
La cucaracha *

10:17.334 --> 10:20.067
* Hey, da-da-da-da-da-da-da *

10:20.067 --> 10:22.200
* La cucaracha
La cucaracha *

10:22.200 --> 10:23.334
Hey.

10:23.334 --> 10:24.934
* Hey!
Da-da-da-da-da-da-da-da *

10:24.934 --> 10:27.534
Hey, amigos, hello.
Can we, like, stop singing

10:27.534 --> 10:29.000
and go get
something to eat here?

10:29.000 --> 10:31.601
Are you crazy? Look
at the progress we're making.

10:31.601 --> 10:33.234
I'm gonna be sick.

10:33.234 --> 10:35.000
Willie, the same thing happened

10:35.000 --> 10:36.801
when my family went to see
my cousin Mindy

10:36.801 --> 10:39.234
in a production of <i>The Best</i>
 <i>Little Whorehouse in Texas.</i>

10:39.234 --> 10:41.934
We were too late to grab dinner
and I ended up barfing

10:41.934 --> 10:43.567
four times on the way
to Sacramento.

10:43.567 --> 10:46.501
Okay, whatever, but we're
only stopping for 10 minutes.

10:46.501 --> 10:47.968
Right. We want to get there
in time

10:47.968 --> 10:49.601
to stake out
a place for the night.

10:49.601 --> 10:51.701
Speaking of which, look,
I just found a great one

10:51.701 --> 10:54.367
right here in the guidebook.
Guidebook?

10:54.367 --> 10:56.467
There's an outdoor pool
and a buffeteria.

10:56.467 --> 10:58.400
Will, you want to help
me out here?

10:58.400 --> 10:59.868
Forget it. Forget it.

10:59.868 --> 11:01.267
There's an in-room coffeemaker.

11:01.267 --> 11:03.968
Now, that's nice. I mean,
that saves time and money.

11:03.968 --> 11:05.300
Will.
Right.

11:05.300 --> 11:07.367
Out of the question.
We're sleeping on the beach

11:07.367 --> 11:08.634
under the stars.
Right.

11:08.634 --> 11:10.300
I don't think so.

11:10.300 --> 11:12.167
That was the whole
point of the trip, Sarah.

11:12.167 --> 11:14.367
What? To sleep outside
where we could get robbed

11:14.367 --> 11:16.767
or murdered or bug bites?
Yes.

11:16.767 --> 11:18.267
I mean, yeah, sort of.

11:18.267 --> 11:21.834
The point is to take
some chances so that someday,

11:21.834 --> 11:23.968
when we have to stay in motels,
we can say that--

11:23.968 --> 11:27.234
That for a few days at least we
were a little bit adventurous.

11:27.234 --> 11:28.701
A-and we kind
of lived by our wits.

11:28.701 --> 11:31.000
And damn it, we handled
whatever came our way.

11:31.000 --> 11:32.267
Anything.

11:32.267 --> 11:34.300
Your engine light just went on.

11:36.434 --> 11:37.801
We're screwed.

11:37.801 --> 11:39.734
[***]

11:43.901 --> 11:45.634
Hey.

11:45.634 --> 11:47.901
Oh, hey.

11:47.901 --> 11:50.868
God, two days in a row, huh?

11:50.868 --> 11:51.868
You looking for me?

11:52.734 --> 11:55.367
No. Uh, no.

11:55.367 --> 11:56.934
I actually have an internship

11:56.934 --> 11:59.033
at a publishing house nearby.

11:59.033 --> 12:00.968
You don't have to explain.

12:00.968 --> 12:03.767
No. I-I know. I just--

12:03.767 --> 12:06.334
S-so, are you having a good time
with all your friends?

12:06.334 --> 12:07.701
Yeah.

12:07.701 --> 12:08.834
Been hanging out a lot.

12:08.834 --> 12:10.667
Stayin' pretty busy.

12:10.667 --> 12:12.601
I mean, that's--
That's why I didn't call--

12:12.601 --> 12:15.334
Oh.
Yeah, yeah, I figured.

12:18.300 --> 12:19.667
A-anyway, uh,

12:19.667 --> 12:22.868
you all doing something great
again tonight?

12:28.334 --> 12:29.400
Do you wanna get together?

12:31.033 --> 12:33.234
You and me?

12:33.234 --> 12:34.634
Uh-huh.

12:34.634 --> 12:37.000
Um, definitely,

12:37.000 --> 12:38.133
If-- If you want to.

12:39.801 --> 12:41.934
Yeah.
Yeah, I want to.

12:45.834 --> 12:48.234
Did she say anything
to you this morning?

12:48.234 --> 12:50.801
Yeah. She, uh--

12:50.801 --> 12:52.601
She told me the mattress sags.

12:55.567 --> 12:56.934
I want her out of here,
Kirsten.

12:57.968 --> 12:59.133
ASAP.

12:59.133 --> 13:00.701
You're not serious.

13:00.701 --> 13:02.334
I can't believe
that you're serious.

13:02.334 --> 13:04.601
Well, believe. That woman
has made it very clear

13:04.601 --> 13:06.801
just how much
she hates my guts.

13:06.801 --> 13:09.300
I'm not inclined to be a tower
of support for her,

13:09.300 --> 13:11.067
whatever it is
she's going through.

13:11.067 --> 13:12.767
Well,
what am I supposed to do, huh?

13:12.767 --> 13:15.000
Say, "Gee, Mom,
sorry your marriage is kaput.

13:15.000 --> 13:15.934
Can I call you a cab?"

13:17.400 --> 13:19.834
Uh, for God's sake,
Charlie, she's a mess.

13:19.834 --> 13:21.567
She's a mess,
and she's my mother.

13:21.567 --> 13:22.634
She needs me.

13:32.167 --> 13:34.334
I did some planting,
did you see?

13:34.334 --> 13:37.434
Hydrangeas don't do well
in direct sun.

13:39.701 --> 13:41.934
Mom, if you don't talk to me,
I'm gonna call Dad.

13:41.934 --> 13:43.133
That's all there is to it.

13:43.133 --> 13:45.434
I had an affair
with Howard Laughton.

13:47.601 --> 13:48.601
What?

13:48.601 --> 13:49.767
Howard Laughton.

13:51.000 --> 13:52.467
Well, you remember him.

13:52.467 --> 13:55.267
He and your daddy
played golf together.

13:55.267 --> 13:57.901
He owns the dealership where
we bought the blue Lincoln.

13:57.901 --> 14:00.734
You--?
You had an affair?

14:00.734 --> 14:03.567
It was, uh, right when
you went away to college.

14:03.567 --> 14:05.601
I was going through
that empty nest thing.

14:05.601 --> 14:08.300
Your daddy was away
on one of his selling seminars.

14:08.300 --> 14:10.801
And Howard and I happened to
run into each other at the club.

14:10.801 --> 14:13.634
I don't want to hear this.
He asked me out to dinner--

14:13.634 --> 14:15.868
I really don't want
to hear this, okay?

14:18.200 --> 14:20.434
No, of course not.
I'm sorry.

14:20.434 --> 14:22.968
It was a mistake, Kirsten.

14:26.033 --> 14:29.167
How did--?
How did Dad--?

14:29.167 --> 14:31.634
Last week he was
fixing my dresser.

14:31.634 --> 14:33.901
The bottom drawer
always sticks.

14:38.400 --> 14:40.033
He found a letter.

14:42.534 --> 14:44.734
From Howard to me.

14:45.734 --> 14:46.834
God.

14:49.934 --> 14:51.334
It was five weeks.

14:54.067 --> 14:55.834
Five weeks, eight years ago.

14:57.267 --> 15:00.834
You hold that
up against 29 years?

15:00.834 --> 15:04.000
Twenty-nine years your father
and I have been together.

15:09.934 --> 15:12.834
Twenty-nine years
and he just

15:12.834 --> 15:17.200
came down the stairs
with my suitcase,

15:17.200 --> 15:21.567
and he put it at the doorstep,
and he asked me for my

15:21.567 --> 15:23.467
house keys back.

15:25.934 --> 15:26.934
Good for him.

15:29.801 --> 15:30.868
[SOBBING]

15:35.000 --> 15:36.267
[DOORBELL RINGS]

15:36.267 --> 15:37.701
Is Griffin coming over?

15:37.701 --> 15:39.968
No. I'm meeting him.
You expecting someone? Coming.

15:39.968 --> 15:41.934
If this is your father,
I'm gonna kill myself.

15:41.934 --> 15:43.901
Yeah, listen, Charlie,
I gotta talk to you.

15:45.067 --> 15:46.734
Can I help you?

15:46.734 --> 15:48.534
I'm Byron.
I'm here to see Claudia.

15:50.801 --> 15:52.100
You're Byron?

15:52.100 --> 15:54.200
Well, she told you
I was coming, right?

15:54.200 --> 15:56.667
Uh, yeah, yeah.
I guess we just, um--

15:56.667 --> 15:58.701
We just all assumed that--

15:58.701 --> 16:00.968
What? That--
That I was making it all up?

16:02.033 --> 16:03.200
I-is that it?

16:03.200 --> 16:04.501
No.
No.
Claud.

16:04.501 --> 16:06.534
CHARLIE:
Claudia, no, no.

16:06.534 --> 16:07.701
Hey.
Hey.

16:08.934 --> 16:11.200
What's going on?
Never mind.

16:11.200 --> 16:14.000
We're going out.

16:14.000 --> 16:15.734
Don't wait up.

16:23.834 --> 16:25.767
GINA:
What was it you said again,
Willie?

16:25.767 --> 16:27.667
Mexico or bust?
Now, there's irony for you.

16:27.667 --> 16:29.400
Hey, hey, hey.
Don't look at me.

16:29.400 --> 16:31.901
He's the one that wouldn't
check the engine before we left.

16:31.901 --> 16:33.801
You know what?
Go ahead. Beat each other up.

16:33.801 --> 16:35.200
I'm gonna go sit
in the tow truck.

16:35.200 --> 16:37.167
Yeah, me too.

16:37.167 --> 16:38.934
What the hell are you blaming me
for, Will?

16:38.934 --> 16:40.767
It's your fault.
My fault?

16:40.767 --> 16:42.534
Hey, you're-- You're
the one who invited

16:42.534 --> 16:45.267
the two killjoy sisters along.
And look at this,

16:45.267 --> 16:47.467
they got us snapping
at each other now.

16:47.467 --> 16:49.501
And-- And I am telling you,

16:49.501 --> 16:52.167
it is a whole
glass-is-half-empty mentality.

16:52.167 --> 16:55.200
You're right. No, you're right.
It's very destructive.

16:55.200 --> 16:56.834
Yes, it is.

16:56.834 --> 16:58.734
I mean-- I mean, so what if--

16:58.734 --> 17:01.767
If we hit a few snags,
a few detours along the way?

17:01.767 --> 17:04.567
So what? You and me,
we take it as it comes.

17:04.567 --> 17:05.867
Right.
Right.

17:05.867 --> 17:07.701
We kick back.

17:07.701 --> 17:09.467
I mean-- I mean,
look at this place.

17:09.467 --> 17:10.834
Really look at it.

17:10.834 --> 17:13.834
This is--
This is very nice scenery.

17:13.834 --> 17:17.634
Well, I can tow you into town,
but I can't get that darn thing

17:17.634 --> 17:19.733
running again till tomorrow.

17:20.501 --> 17:22.133
You're stuck.

17:24.267 --> 17:25.367
No problem.
No problem.

17:27.400 --> 17:29.400
JULIA:
It must have been weird
all these guys

17:29.400 --> 17:30.901
crammed into bunks
with pictures

17:30.901 --> 17:32.934
of their girlfriends
taped up everywhere.

17:32.934 --> 17:34.634
Do you have pictures?

17:34.634 --> 17:36.334
I sent you one of me,

17:36.334 --> 17:38.200
but you never got it.

17:38.200 --> 17:39.200
That's too bad,
huh?

17:40.434 --> 17:43.734
So, um, the internship
really sucks, huh?

17:43.734 --> 17:46.534
Mm. Mostly what I do
is answer phones

17:46.534 --> 17:48.067
and take people's lunch orders.

17:48.067 --> 17:50.567
If the boss doesn't get
hot mustard

17:50.567 --> 17:52.400
with his French dip,
my life is hell.

17:52.400 --> 17:53.567
[LAUGHS]

17:53.567 --> 17:55.167
So I guess
he pretty much deserves

17:55.167 --> 17:56.934
that, uh,
monster comb over, right?

17:56.934 --> 17:58.334
Heh-heh. Yeah, pretty much.

17:58.334 --> 17:59.667
There's this guy
on the boat.

17:59.667 --> 18:01.734
Man, he could win
awards with his.

18:01.734 --> 18:03.767
When the wind blows
the right way, he, uh--

18:03.767 --> 18:07.133
How do you know
Mr. Conklin has a comb over?

18:09.367 --> 18:10.400
You said.

18:10.400 --> 18:11.501
No.

18:11.501 --> 18:12.634
No, I didn't.

18:12.634 --> 18:13.567
Oh, uh,

18:15.200 --> 18:16.801
I-I don't know,
I guess I just figured

18:16.801 --> 18:19.934
a lot of old guys have that lame
hair stuff going on,

18:19.934 --> 18:21.968
right?

18:21.968 --> 18:23.534
I-I wrote you this letter

18:23.534 --> 18:25.901
describing the people
that I work with.

18:30.067 --> 18:32.400
You-- You got my letters,
didn't you?

18:32.400 --> 18:34.734
S-so you knew that
Justin and I broke up?

18:37.067 --> 18:41.300
Y-You've known since--
God, l-last spring.

18:43.267 --> 18:45.167
All those letters,
what did you do with them?

18:45.167 --> 18:47.400
Did you just read them
and throw them away?

18:47.400 --> 18:49.667
No.
I wouldn't do that.

18:49.667 --> 18:52.434
You don't really want
to see me, do you?

18:52.434 --> 18:54.567
No, I-I do.

18:54.567 --> 18:56.834
It's just--

18:56.834 --> 18:58.100
It's just that you didn't know

18:58.100 --> 18:59.434
how to let me down easy.

19:02.067 --> 19:03.434
Well, don't sweat it, Griffin.

19:03.434 --> 19:06.367
You're off the hook.

19:06.367 --> 19:08.400
[***]

19:08.400 --> 19:09.467
[SIGHS]

19:11.868 --> 19:13.501
I just can't get over it.

19:13.501 --> 19:14.701
A car salesman?

19:14.701 --> 19:16.267
I mean, jeez,
who would have thought

19:16.267 --> 19:17.734
your mom would sleep
with someone

19:17.734 --> 19:18.801
who works on commission?

19:18.801 --> 19:20.300
I don't want
to think about it.

19:20.300 --> 19:21.434
I can't think about it.

19:21.434 --> 19:23.234
It's too disgusting
to think about.

19:23.234 --> 19:25.067
She can spend the night,
but that's it.

19:25.067 --> 19:26.634
I mean it.

19:26.634 --> 19:28.267
First thing in the morning:

19:28.267 --> 19:29.601
You're gonna kick her out?

19:29.601 --> 19:32.100
Kirsten, you know,
she didn't cheat on you.

19:32.100 --> 19:34.067
Yes, she did.
Sure, she did.

19:34.067 --> 19:36.133
You see, I always thought

19:36.133 --> 19:38.400
I wanted what my parents had.

19:38.400 --> 19:40.968
It turns out all these years
all they had was this lie

19:40.968 --> 19:43.033
sitting smack in the middle
of their marriage.

19:43.033 --> 19:45.400
Okay. So--
So talk to her about it,

19:45.400 --> 19:48.467
I mean, why it happened,
How to put it in the past.

19:48.467 --> 19:49.467
Work it out.

19:49.467 --> 19:51.567
Work it out?
Hello.

19:51.567 --> 19:53.667
There's nothing
to work out here.

19:53.667 --> 19:55.033
She had an affair.
She cheated.

19:55.033 --> 19:56.601
Nothing's gonna
change that fact.

19:56.601 --> 19:58.000
And that's it?

19:58.000 --> 19:59.601
Eight years ago
she made a mistake

19:59.601 --> 20:01.701
and you plan on never
talking to her again?

20:01.701 --> 20:03.100
Or--
Or forgiving her?

20:03.100 --> 20:06.601
You got it. That's the plan.

20:06.601 --> 20:08.300
Well,
I think that's stupid.

20:08.300 --> 20:10.434
Since when are you on her side,
huh?

20:10.434 --> 20:12.067
She doesn't even like you.

20:12.067 --> 20:14.300
I mean, she hates you.
I mean, she really hates you.

20:14.300 --> 20:17.234
Okay, okay, okay.
You made your point.

20:17.234 --> 20:19.033
God, Charlie,

20:19.033 --> 20:21.367
you're the last person on Earth
who should be on her side.

20:24.868 --> 20:28.000
SARAH:
Gee, wasn't this place
profiled in <i>Travel + Leisure?</i>

20:28.000 --> 20:29.901
Yeah, well,
I happen to love it.

20:29.901 --> 20:31.567
This place--
This place has--

20:31.567 --> 20:33.901
One bed.
It's got one bed, Will.

20:33.901 --> 20:37.300
No, no, no, no. The guy
at the front desk said...

20:37.300 --> 20:40.834
Ah. Ta-da.

20:40.834 --> 20:42.434
You know,
the chances of bed bugs

20:42.434 --> 20:44.701
is significantly greater
if the motel does not have

20:44.701 --> 20:46.434
a major guidebook affiliation.

20:46.434 --> 20:48.934
I didn't see
a sticker in the lobby.

20:48.934 --> 20:51.400
Hm. Neither did I.
But I did see donuts.

20:51.400 --> 20:52.434
Donuts.

20:52.434 --> 20:53.734
Yes!
Yes!

20:53.734 --> 20:55.634
Yeah, maybe I could call
my folks and get them

20:55.634 --> 20:57.400
to put another room
on their credit card.

20:57.400 --> 20:59.868
No way. No way. That's cheating.

21:01.501 --> 21:03.968
Look, what--?
What is the problem here, huh?

21:03.968 --> 21:05.667
We're--
We're all friends, aren't we?

21:05.667 --> 21:07.367
So--
So it's a little snug.

21:07.367 --> 21:09.300
So what?

21:09.300 --> 21:11.067
So what?
We're saving money,

21:11.067 --> 21:13.400
and we're having an adventure.

21:13.400 --> 21:16.200
Hey, Bay, there's a minibar.

21:16.200 --> 21:17.868
Oh-hoh-hoh.
A minibar.

21:17.868 --> 21:19.334
Yes!
Yes!

21:19.334 --> 21:22.267
You know, I never knew I was
capable of such profound hatred.

21:22.267 --> 21:23.501
Staggering, isn't it?

21:23.501 --> 21:25.234
What do you say
the first thing tomorrow

21:25.234 --> 21:27.234
we make them drive us
to the closest bus station

21:27.234 --> 21:28.367
and we head home?

21:28.367 --> 21:29.534
What do I say?

21:30.968 --> 21:31.901
[WITH LOW VOICES]
Yes!

21:33.434 --> 21:35.467
BAILEY:
Yes.

21:38.667 --> 21:39.868
So how'd it go last night?

21:39.868 --> 21:41.100
Fine.

21:41.100 --> 21:42.234
Stay out real late?

21:43.267 --> 21:45.000
Yep.

21:46.868 --> 21:49.067
Claudia, could we just--?

21:49.067 --> 21:50.634
What?
I mean, you don't--

21:50.634 --> 21:52.400
You don't think
I'm actually gonna have

21:52.400 --> 21:56.033
a conversation with
you about Byron, do you?

21:56.033 --> 21:58.701
You know, I can't believe
it took me so long

21:58.701 --> 22:01.567
to figure you guys out. I mean,
the way you were poking around

22:01.567 --> 22:03.968
to find little holes
in my story, or--

22:03.968 --> 22:06.334
O-or the way you
patronized me with that

22:06.334 --> 22:08.300
unbelievable story about camp.

22:08.300 --> 22:09.934
Boy,
talk about transparent.

22:09.934 --> 22:11.167
I'm sorry, Claud.

22:11.167 --> 22:12.434
I didn't mean--
What is it?

22:12.434 --> 22:14.067
I mean, you can't
believe that anyone

22:14.067 --> 22:15.767
would actually
be interested in me?

22:15.767 --> 22:17.133
No, Claud.
No, Claud, come on.

22:17.133 --> 22:18.667
Not at all.

22:18.667 --> 22:19.868
Why is this so impossible

22:19.868 --> 22:22.067
that I could
have feelings about--?

22:22.067 --> 22:26.000
About, you know, guy stuff?
I mean, just because--

22:26.000 --> 22:27.968
I don't know--
I may be small for my age.

22:27.968 --> 22:30.133
Well, I do. Okay?
I-I do have those feelings.

22:33.067 --> 22:34.934
So you better
just get used to it.

22:37.501 --> 22:39.834
[LATIN MUSIC PLAYING]

22:46.467 --> 22:47.567
Huh?

22:49.000 --> 22:50.534
Oh, yeah, incredible.

22:52.200 --> 22:55.300
So, what's the plan?

22:55.300 --> 22:56.634
I don't know.

22:56.634 --> 22:58.567
The girl who
sold me these beers

22:58.567 --> 23:01.334
told me about this--
This cockfight tonight.

23:01.334 --> 23:04.033
This back-alley kind of thing.
It sounds pretty colorful.

23:04.033 --> 23:06.501
She wrote the directions
on my hand. Heh.

23:06.501 --> 23:08.234
That's cute.

23:08.234 --> 23:09.601
You see,

23:09.601 --> 23:12.400
this is the way it should have
been from the start, Will.

23:12.400 --> 23:15.367
I mean, Gina and Sarah
are great, they are, but--

23:15.367 --> 23:17.234
But it's no fun hanging
with people whose--

23:17.234 --> 23:20.334
Whose primary travel objective
is finding a clean bathroom.

23:20.334 --> 23:21.434
Am I right?

23:24.033 --> 23:25.067
Will?

23:25.067 --> 23:26.767
I'm sorry? What?

23:28.767 --> 23:29.701
Journal?

23:31.300 --> 23:33.567
That is so smart.

23:33.567 --> 23:36.133
I should be doing that,
keeping a journal.

23:36.133 --> 23:39.033
You know, writing down
my thoughts, my feelings,

23:39.033 --> 23:41.701
impressions
of the local scenery.

23:41.701 --> 23:43.067
Hi. How's it going?

23:45.467 --> 23:46.701
So go on, read me something.

23:46.701 --> 23:49.868
No. It's stupid. Forget it.

23:49.868 --> 23:52.667
No, I mean it. I mean it.
I want-- I wanna know.

23:52.667 --> 23:56.234
I want to know how you're seeing
this whole trip.

23:56.234 --> 23:58.934
Let me see.

23:58.934 --> 24:02.901
"Lava lamp, lacrosse stick,
Bob Marley poster?"

24:05.000 --> 24:07.634
Just stuff I need to pack
for school when we get back.

24:11.167 --> 24:13.400
So

24:13.400 --> 24:14.634
how about this weather, huh?

24:17.601 --> 24:19.901
Yeah. How about it?

24:31.167 --> 24:32.567
Did you have lunch?

24:32.567 --> 24:34.033
What?

24:34.033 --> 24:37.100
Uh, uh, no.
I'm not hungry.

24:37.100 --> 24:40.367
Okay, so how about if I bring up
something for you anyway?

24:40.367 --> 24:42.901
I-is there no one else
in the house

24:42.901 --> 24:45.033
that you can have
a conversation with right now?

24:45.033 --> 24:47.067
I-is that why you're here?

24:47.067 --> 24:48.501
No.

24:48.501 --> 24:52.100
This is called
trying to be polite.

24:52.100 --> 24:53.968
Yes, I see that.

24:53.968 --> 24:55.100
Why?

24:55.100 --> 24:57.734
I don't know.

24:57.734 --> 25:01.701
All of a sudden it seems like we
have a little bit in common.

25:01.701 --> 25:06.234
I mean, we both made
some mistakes and hurt people.

25:06.234 --> 25:08.767
I don't know what
you're talking about.

25:08.767 --> 25:11.067
All I'm saying is that I know
what it feels like to--

25:11.067 --> 25:13.534
To want to just be forgiven,
you know,

25:13.534 --> 25:15.801
for that one stupid mistake

25:15.801 --> 25:18.000
that you would take back
in, like, a second.

25:18.000 --> 25:21.501
I don't see how
we have a thing in common.

25:22.767 --> 25:24.334
You gotta be kidding me?

25:24.334 --> 25:25.467
You know, just because

25:25.467 --> 25:27.667
I'm having a problem
with my husband,

25:27.667 --> 25:29.968
don't look at me
like you understand,

25:29.968 --> 25:31.801
like we are somehow the same.

25:31.801 --> 25:34.267
I don't make promises
and break them,

25:34.267 --> 25:37.000
over and over again.
Cut it out, okay?

25:37.000 --> 25:40.367
I-I am trying here with you.

25:40.367 --> 25:42.501
And I'm the only one.
Your husband's not

25:42.501 --> 25:44.300
and Kirsten's not,

25:44.300 --> 25:46.701
but I am trying.

25:46.701 --> 25:48.434
Doesn't that count for anything?

25:48.434 --> 25:51.601
No, not in my book.

25:55.734 --> 25:56.934
[SIGHS]

25:58.434 --> 25:59.601
Man.

26:02.701 --> 26:04.067
Can I talk to you?

26:05.267 --> 26:07.634
I only get 30 minutes for lunch.
I gotta go.

26:07.634 --> 26:09.100
Please.
It'll only take a minute.

26:09.100 --> 26:10.767
It's a five-minute walk
to the office.

26:10.767 --> 26:12.033
So you'll be late, okay?

26:14.167 --> 26:15.701
I just--

26:15.701 --> 26:19.868
I just want to let you know that
I didn't toss your letters.

26:21.167 --> 26:22.267
Well, I'm touched.

26:22.267 --> 26:24.133
I read them.

26:24.133 --> 26:25.601
I read every one of them,

26:25.601 --> 26:27.100
over and over.

26:27.100 --> 26:30.167
I nearly drove myself
crazy reading them.

26:30.167 --> 26:32.167
Like, um, th--

26:32.167 --> 26:34.968
This one. Six pages
on how hard it was

26:34.968 --> 26:36.667
for you to break up
with Justin.

26:37.901 --> 26:40.601
Or, uh--
What was it, uh--

26:40.601 --> 26:42.334
This one is,
uh, three pages on

26:42.334 --> 26:44.634
taking Claudia to camp.

26:44.634 --> 26:46.767
Well, I'm sorry
I was boring you.

26:46.767 --> 26:48.901
No, that's not--

26:48.901 --> 26:52.334
You don't--
You're not getting it.

26:52.334 --> 26:56.434
I-I just kept waiting
for you to write, uh,

26:56.434 --> 26:59.133
"I miss you,"
or, "I wish you were here,"

26:59.133 --> 27:00.100
or,

27:01.767 --> 27:03.968
I don't know,
"I love you," or something,

27:03.968 --> 27:06.367
but you didn't.

27:06.367 --> 27:08.767
It was always,
"Hope you're okay,"

27:08.767 --> 27:11.634
or, uh,
"Write me if you feel like it."

27:13.767 --> 27:15.667
That's the stuff
you write to a friend.

27:15.667 --> 27:17.234
You know, just a friend.

27:17.234 --> 27:21.367
So I didn't know what you were
thinking about me.

27:27.300 --> 27:29.033
[***]

27:30.534 --> 27:32.834
You know that, uh,

27:32.834 --> 27:34.901
letter about Claudia?

27:34.901 --> 27:37.667
It's the one
with the picture in it.

27:39.300 --> 27:41.467
Yeah. It's...

27:43.133 --> 27:45.267
It's okay
to put that by your bed.

27:47.868 --> 27:48.801
Yeah?

27:55.501 --> 27:57.934
WILL:
I'm telling you, Bailey,
this is not the street.

27:57.934 --> 27:59.501
We drove past here an hour ago.

27:59.501 --> 28:01.501
That, "Gringo, go home"
graffiti,

28:01.501 --> 28:02.801
does it ring any bells?
Okay.

28:02.801 --> 28:04.567
So it's not a great
neighborhood, Will.

28:04.567 --> 28:07.000
So what? We're not going
to visit your grandma.

28:07.000 --> 28:10.033
We're going to watch roosters
peck each other to death.

28:10.033 --> 28:11.434
Do you see a number?

28:11.434 --> 28:13.334
What are we looking for?

28:13.334 --> 28:15.334
Here.

28:15.334 --> 28:17.601
What, do you need some
change or something?

28:17.601 --> 28:20.400
The address of this place,
that girl wrote it on my palm.

28:21.634 --> 28:23.267
Ow, ow.
Take it easy, Will.

28:23.267 --> 28:25.300
I can't read it.
It's all smudged.

28:25.300 --> 28:27.167
Couldn't have copied it on
a piece of paper?

28:27.167 --> 28:28.834
Okay, okay. So I'm not
as anal as you are

28:28.834 --> 28:30.501
about writing stuff down.
I'm sorry.

28:31.801 --> 28:33.100
Okay, remind me again,

28:33.100 --> 28:35.667
the problem with stopping
and asking for directions is...?

28:35.667 --> 28:36.901
Directions are for people

28:36.901 --> 28:38.601
who only care about where
they're going,

28:38.601 --> 28:40.234
not where they
are in the moment.

28:40.234 --> 28:41.934
Directions are for people--
I get it.

28:41.934 --> 28:44.033
Okay, Bay? I get it.

28:51.367 --> 28:52.767
The airline.

28:52.767 --> 28:54.968
I'll be out of your hair
first thing in the morning.

28:56.934 --> 28:59.534
Where are you gonna stay
when you get back to Chicago?

28:59.534 --> 29:02.067
Your sister has that
room over the garage.

29:02.067 --> 29:04.067
Might be a good excuse
for her to dust.

29:05.934 --> 29:08.567
I expect I'll get the same
kind of reception from her.

29:19.000 --> 29:21.801
T-this is what
I don't understand.

29:21.801 --> 29:23.734
You and Charlie,

29:23.734 --> 29:25.834
all the terrible things
he did to you

29:27.501 --> 29:29.067
and you've forgiven him.

29:30.701 --> 29:31.634
Why?

29:32.767 --> 29:34.634
Because I love him.

29:39.300 --> 29:41.534
[SOBBING]

29:41.534 --> 29:43.267
Don't you love me?

29:43.267 --> 29:45.000
Mom.

29:45.000 --> 29:46.901
Because I love you, Kirsten.

29:48.834 --> 29:50.067
So much.

29:51.801 --> 29:55.501
And your sister
and your father so much.

29:57.200 --> 29:59.267
I don't want
to lose any of you.

29:59.267 --> 30:03.167
Please, please,
do not walk away from me.

30:03.167 --> 30:05.601
I mean,
if you can forgive a man

30:05.601 --> 30:08.400
who left you at the altar,
why can't you forgive me?

30:08.400 --> 30:09.734
I don't know.

30:09.734 --> 30:11.934
I've been trying
to figure that out myself.

30:13.634 --> 30:17.434
Maybe I don't feel
like being generous, Mom,

30:17.434 --> 30:20.367
because what you want from me
you can't give in return.

30:21.934 --> 30:23.334
I don't know what you mean.

30:25.100 --> 30:26.701
Why can't I forgive you?

30:26.701 --> 30:28.234
Why can't you forgive him?

30:29.400 --> 30:30.467
Well, please, no, that--

30:30.467 --> 30:32.501
That's different. It's--

30:32.501 --> 30:34.934
No, it isn't.
It's exactly the same.

30:36.801 --> 30:39.400
Do you know how much
I want you and Daddy

30:39.400 --> 30:41.434
to be together and happy?

30:41.434 --> 30:45.133
Well, I do, Mom.
More than anything.

30:47.634 --> 30:51.300
But I want you to wish
the same for me and Charlie.

30:54.334 --> 30:56.434
And I want you to go first.

30:57.934 --> 31:01.133
Gee, I always thought that
was just a figure of speech,

31:01.133 --> 31:03.334
but, you know,
chickens really do run around

31:03.334 --> 31:05.067
for a long time
without their heads on.

31:05.067 --> 31:07.434
Yeah, I kind of had trouble
enjoying the scene after that.

31:08.501 --> 31:09.567
Where'd we leave the car?

31:09.567 --> 31:10.834
I thought it was right here.

31:10.834 --> 31:12.601
You don't remember
where we left the car?

31:12.601 --> 31:15.167
I remember, Will,
it was right around here.

31:16.234 --> 31:17.534
What the--?

31:17.534 --> 31:19.534
What's that?

31:19.534 --> 31:20.567
What?

31:23.133 --> 31:25.033
It's your window, I think.

31:25.033 --> 31:27.033
What?

31:27.033 --> 31:28.567
No way.

31:28.567 --> 31:31.667
Ugh.
Oh, no.

31:31.667 --> 31:33.567
I don't believe it.

31:33.567 --> 31:34.801
Damn it.

31:43.400 --> 31:45.734
Is there--? Is there something
you want to say, Will?

31:45.734 --> 31:48.934
Huh? You want to clue me in
why you're acting like

31:48.934 --> 31:51.200
it's my fault that
my jeep just got stolen?

31:51.200 --> 31:52.701
Of course
it's not your fault, Bay.

31:52.701 --> 31:54.667
Just because you got us
wandering around here

31:54.667 --> 31:56.567
in the middle of the night
searching for some

31:56.567 --> 31:58.634
freak-infested
animal torture event.

31:58.634 --> 32:00.767
just because some idiot girl
came on to you.

32:00.767 --> 32:02.634
You know what, Will?
If you didn't want to do

32:02.634 --> 32:05.067
anything more daring than watch
videos and eat popcorn,

32:05.067 --> 32:06.601
why didn't you just stay home?

32:06.601 --> 32:08.834
Good question,
'cause you're going nuts.

32:08.834 --> 32:11.400
I don't know what you're trying
to prove. I don't wanna end up

32:11.400 --> 32:12.901
in a body bag.
I gotta go to college.

32:12.901 --> 32:15.267
See, now, now we get
to the real point.

32:15.267 --> 32:16.534
Your going to college.

32:16.534 --> 32:18.400
You don't give a damn about
this trip, Will.

32:18.400 --> 32:20.000
You never did.
You're right. Right.

32:20.000 --> 32:22.400
You just figured me out.
Why don't you just go home?

32:22.400 --> 32:25.234
Point me to the bus station.
Point yourself.

32:25.234 --> 32:26.767
I'm gonna keep going.

32:26.767 --> 32:27.901
Really, Bay?

32:27.901 --> 32:29.167
Yeah, really.

32:29.167 --> 32:31.601
You got no stuff, you got
no car, you got no money.

32:31.601 --> 32:33.868
This trip's history.
You're done.

32:40.033 --> 32:40.968
[SIGHS]

32:44.934 --> 32:46.434
You want to go somewhere?

32:47.434 --> 32:49.868
Mm-mm.

32:49.868 --> 32:51.267
This is nice.

32:56.167 --> 32:58.133
This is nice,
don't you think?

32:58.133 --> 32:59.667
Yeah.

33:06.767 --> 33:07.701
What?

33:08.767 --> 33:10.033
Nothing.

33:13.834 --> 33:15.667
Wait.

33:17.167 --> 33:18.734
What's the matter?

33:18.734 --> 33:21.000
Don't--?
Don't you want to do this?

33:21.000 --> 33:23.467
Don't you want to kiss me?

33:25.334 --> 33:26.300
I don't know.

33:28.033 --> 33:29.200
What?

33:29.200 --> 33:30.567
[SIGHS]

33:30.567 --> 33:33.868
God, Griffin,

33:33.868 --> 33:35.934
what is going on with you?

33:35.934 --> 33:39.100
I mean,
this afternoon I thought--

33:40.534 --> 33:42.167
I don't know
what you want from me.

33:42.167 --> 33:44.501
What are you talking about?

33:44.501 --> 33:46.133
I'm in love with you.

33:48.200 --> 33:50.100
So, what are you doing,
then?

33:50.100 --> 33:52.200
A-are you playing
games with me

33:52.200 --> 33:54.934
because I-I don't understand.
I really don't.

33:54.934 --> 33:57.667
T-this afternoon

33:57.667 --> 34:01.200
when we talked,

34:01.200 --> 34:03.167
it-- It made me happy.

34:03.167 --> 34:07.067
I mean, like--
Like, really, really happy.

34:07.067 --> 34:08.501
Y-You don't even know.

34:11.199 --> 34:13.634
Then I started thinking
about it.

34:13.634 --> 34:15.868
Thinking about us.

34:15.868 --> 34:18.132
I kind of freaked out

34:19.367 --> 34:20.400
because,

34:20.400 --> 34:24.100
you see...

34:24.100 --> 34:25.934
All this time that there were--

34:25.934 --> 34:28.900
There were all these things
that were in the way,

34:28.900 --> 34:31.000
you know,
now there's nothing.

34:31.000 --> 34:32.400
It's--

34:32.400 --> 34:34.868
Now it's just up to me.

34:34.868 --> 34:37.734
[***]

34:37.734 --> 34:41.234
And if I don't
get it right this time,

34:41.234 --> 34:43.467
it's over.

34:43.467 --> 34:44.501
I have nothing.

34:44.501 --> 34:46.567
Griffin, y-you can't--

34:46.567 --> 34:48.501
I don't want to have nothing.

35:03.634 --> 35:05.567
[CHATTER]

35:07.434 --> 35:08.801
Hey, Jule.

35:08.801 --> 35:10.234
Hey.

35:10.234 --> 35:12.467
Aren't you supposed
to be in Mexico?

35:12.467 --> 35:14.334
Yeah.
So, what's your point?

35:14.334 --> 35:16.567
Well, when did you get back?
I didn't see the jeep.

35:16.567 --> 35:18.133
Stolen.

35:18.133 --> 35:20.067
I had to take
the damn bus back.

35:20.067 --> 35:21.400
Oh, yeah?

35:22.767 --> 35:25.334
No. See, that's--
That's a big deal.

35:25.334 --> 35:27.501
The jeep was stolen.

35:27.501 --> 35:28.667
Julia.

35:32.634 --> 35:33.834
Where's Griffin?

35:33.834 --> 35:35.968
Hm?

35:35.968 --> 35:37.234
Where's Griffin?

35:37.234 --> 35:38.868
Oh.

35:38.868 --> 35:40.434
I don't know.
I haven't seen him.

35:42.133 --> 35:46.033
Maybe he's out there. Maybe he's
on one of those ships.

35:46.033 --> 35:47.400
One of those could be his.

35:51.567 --> 35:53.400
So I'm guessing things
didn't go so great.

35:54.434 --> 35:56.601
Hm.
I don't know.

35:56.601 --> 35:59.467
Maybe it's not
such a bad thing, huh?

35:59.467 --> 36:01.868
I mean,
it's like what's past is past,

36:01.868 --> 36:05.167
and now I'm completely open
to meeting someone great.

36:05.167 --> 36:07.901
I mean, maybe I'll meet someone
great at this party.

36:10.667 --> 36:11.901
[SCOFFS]

36:11.901 --> 36:14.234
Or maybe I'll just
take a breather.

36:17.901 --> 36:19.334
To summer fun.

36:21.300 --> 36:23.133
Summer fun.

36:36.367 --> 36:37.934
I've got a cab waiting.

36:37.934 --> 36:40.467
I just came to say goodbye.

36:40.467 --> 36:43.267
And to thank me
for my hospitality, right?

36:43.267 --> 36:47.501
Look, um, I've got
a lot of work do, so...

36:47.501 --> 36:49.834
I hope you're happy, Charlie.

36:49.834 --> 36:51.734
Wow.

36:51.734 --> 36:53.167
No, no.

36:53.167 --> 36:55.167
I-I mean,
I hope you'll be happy.

36:55.167 --> 36:56.100
You and Kirsten.

36:57.167 --> 36:58.501
You do?

36:58.501 --> 37:00.067
Since when?

37:02.634 --> 37:03.868
I'm sorry

37:05.367 --> 37:07.400
about yesterday.

37:10.467 --> 37:13.634
I'm going to get off your back,
Charlie.

37:14.968 --> 37:17.834
No more letters
and no more insults.

37:18.868 --> 37:20.701
I promise.
That's great, Ellie.

37:20.701 --> 37:22.734
That's just great.

37:22.734 --> 37:24.634
I-I thought that's
what you wanted?

37:24.634 --> 37:27.300
I guess I'm kind of past the
point of being grateful to you

37:27.300 --> 37:29.234
for not telling me
what a loser I am.

37:29.234 --> 37:31.267
Oh, for God's sake,
Charlie, I never meant--

37:31.267 --> 37:33.267
It's not enough to stop being
negative, Ellie.

37:33.267 --> 37:34.901
Then what?

37:34.901 --> 37:36.267
What is it you want?

37:36.267 --> 37:39.267
I-I want you to give me
some credit for once.

37:39.267 --> 37:41.234
Just actually say,
"Yeah, Charlie, you--

37:41.234 --> 37:44.000
"You've made mistakes but you're
turning things around.

37:44.000 --> 37:45.834
"And you're doing okay.

37:45.834 --> 37:47.200
"You're being responsible,

37:47.200 --> 37:49.234
and I can see
why she loves you."

37:49.234 --> 37:50.434
You know?

37:50.434 --> 37:53.834
I-it just would have been
nice if you--

37:53.834 --> 37:56.834
Well,
it just would have been nice,

37:56.834 --> 37:59.901
but I guess
that's just the way it is.

38:01.834 --> 38:03.400
I hope.

38:05.000 --> 38:06.367
[SIGHS]

38:06.367 --> 38:08.934
I hope that my husband loves me

38:10.434 --> 38:12.334
as much as my daughter
loves you.

38:17.601 --> 38:19.167
I hope so too.

38:21.133 --> 38:22.501
I don't know.

38:22.501 --> 38:24.868
I guess--
I guess I just figured

38:24.868 --> 38:26.801
it was our last
hurrah together,

38:26.801 --> 38:27.968
mine and Will's.

38:27.968 --> 38:29.467
But you know what?

38:30.968 --> 38:32.100
He didn't need one.

38:33.534 --> 38:34.667
And you did, huh?

38:37.601 --> 38:39.467
Hey, you know,
I-I was thinking,

38:39.467 --> 38:41.100
if you want
maybe in a couple of weeks,

38:41.100 --> 38:42.400
we could drive up to Yosemite,

38:42.400 --> 38:44.868
do some hiking
before the weather turns?

38:44.868 --> 38:46.501
Yeah, maybe.

38:48.033 --> 38:52.033
You and I can make all kinds
of plans together if you want.

38:52.033 --> 38:53.801
I mean, you know,
we can do stuff

38:53.801 --> 38:55.167
that you'll remember for years.

38:56.734 --> 38:58.901
Hey, I can--
I can learn how to chug beer

38:58.901 --> 39:00.634
and belch
and do guy stuff like that.

39:00.634 --> 39:02.133
You know,
slap you on the back a lot,

39:02.133 --> 39:04.167
stop expressing my feelings.

39:04.167 --> 39:05.801
That'd be good?

39:06.868 --> 39:08.868
That'd be great.

39:08.868 --> 39:10.701
Wouldn't be the same,
but it'd be great.

39:10.701 --> 39:13.467
Yeah, yeah, I know,
big shoes to fill.

39:13.467 --> 39:15.901
But I don't know,

39:15.901 --> 39:18.634
I kind of like the idea
of being your best friend.

39:21.734 --> 39:24.167
You're my best friend.

39:27.133 --> 39:28.801
Okay.

39:28.801 --> 39:30.901
Let's get started.

39:30.901 --> 39:32.067
[GIGGLES]

39:32.067 --> 39:33.334
Okay.

39:35.801 --> 39:37.234
[BELCHES]

39:39.467 --> 39:41.234
I can do this.

39:41.234 --> 39:42.334
[BELCHES]

39:42.334 --> 39:44.033
Heh-heh, nice.

39:46.834 --> 39:47.934
[BELCHES]

39:47.934 --> 39:50.267
[ROCK MUSIC PLAYING ON STEREO]

39:50.267 --> 39:51.567
BYRON:
Coach says I gotta drop

39:51.567 --> 39:53.167
my goals-against average
this year.

39:53.167 --> 39:55.934
That means I gotta focus
more on the fundamentals.

39:55.934 --> 39:57.734
Fundamentals?

39:57.734 --> 40:00.434
Great.

40:00.434 --> 40:02.567
What are the fundamentals?

40:02.567 --> 40:04.801
Hey, are you cold?
Do you want my jacket?

40:06.033 --> 40:07.467
Yeah.

40:07.467 --> 40:08.801
Sure.

40:08.801 --> 40:10.100
Okay, So, uh--

40:10.100 --> 40:11.501
So where was I?

40:11.501 --> 40:12.868
The fundamentals.

40:12.868 --> 40:15.501
Oh, right, right.
Well, there's a bunch of them.

40:15.501 --> 40:18.634
There's speed, stamina,
uh, ball-handling,

40:18.634 --> 40:21.634
shot-blocking and effective
playmaking technique.

40:21.634 --> 40:23.234
That last one's
kind of my best thing.

40:23.234 --> 40:24.734
The coach says
I still need to make

40:24.734 --> 40:26.567
more of my own
opportunities, you know?

40:26.567 --> 40:27.567
Anyway...

40:34.033 --> 40:35.067
They were running out.

40:37.534 --> 40:38.601
Thanks.

40:41.234 --> 40:43.300
You're an incredible jerk,
you know that?

40:43.300 --> 40:45.901
Yeah, well, I could say
the same thing about you.

40:45.901 --> 40:49.033
Really? I swear to God
my mother is taking

40:49.033 --> 40:50.801
this college stuff
better than you.

40:50.801 --> 40:53.534
'Cause she can't wait for you to
get the hell out of her house.

40:53.534 --> 40:55.267
That's true.

40:57.200 --> 40:59.567
Look, Bay,
I know what you're thinking.

40:59.567 --> 41:01.434
You're like, "Oh, man,
he gets to go away,

41:01.434 --> 41:03.567
start again,
the whole thing."

41:03.567 --> 41:06.334
But really
you've already done that.

41:06.334 --> 41:08.567
You know, y-you, like,
grew up years ago.

41:08.567 --> 41:09.868
You sort of had to.

41:09.868 --> 41:12.767
And now I'm just
kind of catching up.

41:18.934 --> 41:20.334
Look at this.

41:20.334 --> 41:21.434
This is ridiculous.

41:22.868 --> 41:24.067
We're standing by the ocean

41:24.067 --> 41:25.868
in the freaking moonlight.

41:25.868 --> 41:28.267
Yeah.

41:28.267 --> 41:31.000
Pretty soon the violins
are gonna start playing.

41:32.434 --> 41:33.801
[BOTH LAUGH]

41:37.100 --> 41:38.133
[SIGHS]

41:38.133 --> 41:39.234
I don't know.

41:40.701 --> 41:42.968
Ten years, one best friend.

41:45.200 --> 41:47.567
That's pretty impressive.

41:47.567 --> 41:50.334
I mean, that's never
gonna happen again.

41:54.567 --> 41:56.334
It's not gonna change,
Bay.

41:59.067 --> 42:01.667
Some stuff just doesn't change.

42:14.434 --> 42:16.601
[SLOW ROCK MUSIC
PLAYING ON STEREO]

42:21.200 --> 42:22.634
They're out of beer.

42:23.634 --> 42:25.367
What?

42:25.367 --> 42:28.133
I mean, who throws a party and
runs out of beer before 10:00?

42:28.133 --> 42:30.300
[SCOFFS]

42:30.300 --> 42:31.801
What are you doing, Griffin?

42:31.801 --> 42:33.968
Are you dropping by to kvetch
or are you--?

42:33.968 --> 42:35.534
I was planning on staying,

42:35.534 --> 42:37.667
But after this whole
beer thing, who knows.

42:38.667 --> 42:40.033
[SCOFFS]

42:40.033 --> 42:40.968
Great.

42:43.400 --> 42:44.767
You know,

42:44.767 --> 42:48.334
it's not like this isn't scary
for me.

42:48.334 --> 42:52.634
It's not like I'm not taking
a big chance with you too.

42:52.634 --> 42:54.934
I mean, you flake out,

42:54.934 --> 42:57.200
and then you drop back in
and then you flake out again,

42:57.200 --> 42:59.267
and I really wish you--
I'm staying in.

42:59.267 --> 43:02.267
I'm staying.
Okay, Julia?

43:05.200 --> 43:07.701
I mean, I just can't--
I can't not.

43:09.868 --> 43:13.300
So whatever happens,

43:13.300 --> 43:14.434
I'll risk it.

43:19.534 --> 43:20.901
Okay.

43:29.534 --> 43:32.501
I wonder if one of those little
dots out there is my ship.

43:36.167 --> 43:38.400
Ah, who cares.

43:43.734 --> 43:46.534
 <i>* Have I said too much? *</i>

43:46.534 --> 43:49.601
 <i>* Have I blown my cover? *</i>

43:49.601 --> 43:53.400
 <i>* My Indian summer *</i>

43:53.400 --> 43:56.167
 <i>* I can feel it in the air *</i>

43:58.200 --> 44:00.133
